metadata.name: Henoheno Samurai #2388
metadata.description:
This work was inspired by Otsu-e(大津絵), a Japanese painting in the Edo period. Otsu-e were inexpensive paintings made as souvenirs. Although mass-produced using paper stencils, the artisans painted by hand, resulting in variations in the quality of their work. Connoisseurs found them interesting and collected them as works of art. Otsu-e showed a new value of beauty in Japanese art, different from Ukiyo-e (浮世絵) which are prints, and from fine art paintings which are one-of-a-kind artworks.

This work is made of canvas2D Bezier curves. Not just a combination of parts, but also a random displacement of the Bezier curve points to lose the shape. This is intended to create fun with the Otsu-e-like effect.


Features:
This profile is made up of 8 parts (brows, eyes, nose, mouth, ear, contour, hair, and body). Each part has 100 basic types. 
There are 7 skin colors and 12 kimono colors. Each RGB value of the colors is randomly added within a range of ±10. In addition, there are 70 kimono patterns. 
The distortion rate due to displacement of Bezier curve points is 0.0~50.0. 


BTW The title "Henoheno" is taken from the Japanese character picture "Henohenomoheji" known since the Edo period.

metadata.name: Misunderstanding #332
metadata.description:
Each color/stripe represents a single person or a group of people, trying to communicate with each other. But their attempts in an understandable and agreeable communication are mostly always misaligned. Hence, none of them understand each other as they want to be understood. And for that, some of them don't even bother trying to communicate at all.

* * *

Happy anniversary! #fxhashturnsone

Press S to save as PNG. To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL, press Enter and then press S.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #2368
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.

metadata.name: Rue Parisienne #55
metadata.description:
Batist & Popeye joins forces to present a collection at the crossroads of street art and digital collage, mixing the artistic universe of one and the other.

After putting fake web3 street names in Paris, Batist & Popeye now invite you to collect them in the form of NFTs:
- Avenue Vitalik Buterin
- Passage Hic Et Nunc
- Place du Rug Pull
- Chemin du Petit Shitcoin
- Allée des Cryptopunks

Every hash generates a unique visual collage out of an infinity possible combinations.

metadata.name: Time #30
metadata.description:
To pass time while in meetings or just trying to solve a problem I like to sketch on my notebook continuous abstract lines, usually following a short pattern without paying too much attention to the process. 

In this project I take this to the extreme in a generative approach. The resulting image is one continuous line imperfectly repeating the same pattern for a minute. You can travel back in time and zoom in to explore all layers.

Instructions:

- use the mouse to navigate (zoom, pan and drag)
- press 'c' to switch between multiple camera angles
- press 't' to switch time travel mode (use your mouse to go back in time)
- press 'p' in 'Open live' to download the current view it in a custom resolution. This usually results in better quality for prints.

Berlin, January 2022
@bgola

Like a timeless botany book, ancient and futuristic at the same time, which illustrates the magic of generative emergence, with an illustrated sampler of real but impossible gardens.

Randomness, geometric algorithms and space colonization techniques intertwine to generate infinite maps of fantastic gardens, where only the mind can wander.

---

metadata.name: Territory A #42
metadata.description:
Territory is a recurring theme in my visual experiments. In Territory A, two main patterns slowly trade space:

As cells empty, they eventually host simple lines, drawn together in a few restricted angles to form naive patterns. As cells instead fill up, they grow into organized grids of towers. When they reach their highest possible value, they attempt to link to each and often devolve into a different form of chaos.

These sketches are animated deterministically from the current time. Their composition is unique at any point in time. You can press the space bar to pause the viewer, and again to return it to the current time.

Territory A is *entirely* responsive. Note that aspect ratios that are very far from a square can be taxing on your hardware, as there's much more cells being drawn.
